00:00:09.573 --> 00:00:16.079
1970, TOKYO, JAPAN

00:00:19.750 --> 00:00:23.712
Take
the first flight out to Fukuoka tomorrow.

00:00:24.671 --> 00:00:27.424
When you get there,
someone will be waiting for you.

00:00:31.428 --> 00:00:32.763
And who would that be?

00:00:34.681 --> 00:00:37.476
I want you to meet Ikeda Yuji
and hand over this briefcase.

00:00:45.108 --> 00:00:46.234
Ikeda Yuji?

00:00:47.277 --> 00:00:48.987
Your business partner.

00:00:50.864 --> 00:00:53.325
The moment you
fall out of favor with Ikeda,

00:00:54.242 --> 00:00:55.619
the deal's over.

00:01:03.919 --> 00:01:05.545
A BUSINESSMAN

00:01:12.177 --> 00:01:13.887
My name is Matsuda Kenji,

00:01:14.638 --> 00:01:17.140
a businessman on a work trip to Fukuoka.

00:01:19.851 --> 00:01:23.689
My job is to deliver this briefcase safely
to Ikeda Yuji.

00:01:32.572 --> 00:01:35.075
Hey, are you not feeling well?

00:01:35.158 --> 00:01:36.868
Are you scared to fly?

00:01:37.703 --> 00:01:38.995
- I'm not scared.
- Hmm?

00:01:39.579 --> 00:01:41.373
It's just my first time.

00:01:41.998 --> 00:01:45.460
Everyone feels that way
their first time flying.

00:01:46.086 --> 00:01:50.382
During takeoff,
your ears might pop a little.

00:01:52.050 --> 00:01:54.094
It helps if you chew gum.

00:01:57.389 --> 00:01:58.765
What do you say?

00:01:58.849 --> 00:02:00.350
Thank you.

00:02:01.935 --> 00:02:02.936
Good for you.

00:02:06.440 --> 00:02:09.443
Good morning, ladies
and gentlemen. This flight is scheduled…

00:02:09.526 --> 00:02:12.362
Japan Airways 351 cleared for takeoff.

00:02:12.446 --> 00:02:13.739
Runway 33.

00:02:13.822 --> 00:02:14.823
Stabilized.

00:02:14.906 --> 00:02:17.159
…and arrive at Fukuoka Itazuke Airport

00:02:17.242 --> 00:02:18.243
at around 8:50 a.m.

00:02:18.326 --> 00:02:19.828
We will be taking off shortly.

00:02:19.911 --> 00:02:24.166
Please be seated
and fasten your seat belt.

00:02:24.249 --> 00:02:25.959
We will be taking off shortly.

00:02:26.042 --> 00:02:30.464
Please be seated
and fasten your seat belt.

00:02:32.424 --> 00:02:34.009
Set takeoff thrust.

00:02:34.092 --> 00:02:35.260
Set takeoff thrust.

00:02:35.844 --> 00:02:36.887
Thrust set.

00:02:36.970 --> 00:02:38.013
Check.

00:02:51.818 --> 00:02:54.863
Japan Airways 351, Haneda departure.

00:02:54.946 --> 00:02:58.700
Contact Tokyo Control 134.1.

00:02:59.201 --> 00:03:00.202
Good day.

00:03:04.790 --> 00:03:06.041
Sure.

00:03:12.172 --> 00:03:13.882
Would you like something to drink?

00:03:13.965 --> 00:03:16.051
- Cola, please.
- Sure.

00:03:19.596 --> 00:03:20.847
- Here you go.
- Thanks.

00:03:21.765 --> 00:03:23.183
Oh, excuse me.

00:03:27.896 --> 00:03:29.523
Would you like something to drink?

00:04:02.013 --> 00:04:03.181
Good morning.

00:04:10.522 --> 00:04:11.773
Nobody move!

00:04:11.856 --> 00:04:13.525
Don't move!

00:04:13.608 --> 00:04:15.902
Move!

00:04:16.486 --> 00:04:17.946
Don't move, or you're dead!

00:04:18.738 --> 00:04:20.365
Don't move!

00:04:21.199 --> 00:04:23.535
Mayday, mayday,
hijacking, hijacking.

00:04:23.618 --> 00:04:25.120
- This is Japan Air…
- Stop.

00:04:25.203 --> 00:04:28.415
We're the Revolutionary Army
of the Communist League.

00:04:28.498 --> 00:04:29.833
Please don't kill me! Please!

00:04:29.916 --> 00:04:31.585
Shut up and keep your heads down!

00:04:32.544 --> 00:04:33.837
Heads down!

00:04:35.297 --> 00:04:37.632
We're going to North Korea.

00:04:38.133 --> 00:04:39.968
- Shut up!
- Hey!

00:04:40.051 --> 00:04:41.386
Mom.

00:04:42.804 --> 00:04:44.598
Are we going to die?

00:04:47.100 --> 00:04:48.143
Shut up!

00:04:48.226 --> 00:04:49.227
It's okay.

00:04:49.936 --> 00:04:52.856
You and your mom
will make it out of here safely.

00:04:54.691 --> 00:04:57.027
Shut up!

00:04:57.110 --> 00:04:58.403
Japan Airways Flight 351,

00:04:58.486 --> 00:05:03.700
a Japanese airliner that
left Tokyo Haneda Airport for Fukuoka

00:05:04.409 --> 00:05:07.162
with 138 passengers and crew on board,
was hijacked midair.

00:05:09.247 --> 00:05:10.999
The hijackers were the Revolutionary Army,

00:05:11.082 --> 00:05:13.460
a radical leftist offshoot
of the Japanese Communist League,

00:05:13.543 --> 00:05:15.587
calling themselves
the "Army for Revolutionary War."

00:05:16.338 --> 00:05:19.090
They returned to Japan
after military training in North Korea,

00:05:19.966 --> 00:05:24.179
and hijacked a civilian airliner,
intent on launching a revolutionary war.

00:05:24.679 --> 00:05:27.015
Heads down! Down!

00:06:22.570 --> 00:06:25.740
MINISTRY OF TRANSPORT, JAPAN

00:06:28.785 --> 00:06:31.496
URGENT REPORT, AIRCRAFT HIJACKING

00:06:31.579 --> 00:06:32.998
We're assessing the situation,

00:06:33.081 --> 00:06:35.542
- but it's not clear yet.
- Please hold on for a moment.

00:06:35.625 --> 00:06:39.713
- Hey! No one answer the phone!
- Don't answer the phone!

00:06:39.796 --> 00:06:41.006
Hey, hang up! Hang up!

00:06:42.465 --> 00:06:46.011
We lost all contact
after the captain's distress signal.

00:06:46.094 --> 00:06:47.095
I see.

00:06:47.178 --> 00:06:48.805
MINISTER OF TRANSPORT
MORIYAMA YOSHIRO

00:06:48.888 --> 00:06:50.598
So, what do you think we should do now?

00:06:51.099 --> 00:06:52.809
VICE-MINISTER OF TRANSPORT
NATSUME JUNJI

00:06:52.892 --> 00:06:55.562
We should probably report this
to the Cabinet first.

00:06:55.645 --> 00:06:56.688
Right.

00:06:57.564 --> 00:07:00.275
Then let's draft a report right away.

00:07:01.860 --> 00:07:04.821
The Revolutionary Army boarded
the plane with loads of guns and knives

00:07:04.904 --> 00:07:06.573
with no trouble at all.

00:07:07.240 --> 00:07:10.118
Before that,
how about we notify the police first, sir?

00:07:11.035 --> 00:07:12.454
That's a good point too.

00:07:13.246 --> 00:07:18.376
But I'm not sure who we should call first,
Tokyo or Fukuoka police…

00:07:18.460 --> 00:07:21.546
Back then, there were
no security checks before boarding.

00:07:22.172 --> 00:07:23.631
A manual for hijackings?

00:07:23.715 --> 00:07:26.050
Guess we'll have to check
for precedent first, huh?

00:07:26.134 --> 00:07:28.428
There was no such thing.

00:07:28.511 --> 00:07:31.055
Well,
the report should probably be addressed

00:07:31.139 --> 00:07:32.807
to the Prime Minister, right?

00:07:33.391 --> 00:07:35.477
That's another thing we'll need to check.

00:07:35.977 --> 00:07:36.978
Good point.

00:07:38.480 --> 00:07:39.481
But…

00:07:41.107 --> 00:07:44.110
are we sure
there's been an actual hijacking?

00:07:44.694 --> 00:07:46.196
Yes, sir. It's confirmed.

00:07:51.242 --> 00:07:52.994
Keep your heads down!

00:07:53.077 --> 00:07:55.246
Drop your hands, and you're done for!

00:07:55.747 --> 00:07:56.915
Keep your heads down!

00:07:58.082 --> 00:07:59.584
Turbulence.

00:07:59.667 --> 00:08:01.419
We could go into a stall!

00:08:02.629 --> 00:08:04.964
-Should we change course?
-What are you up to?

00:08:05.048 --> 00:08:07.675
The weather's getting worse,
and the aircraft is unstable.

00:08:07.759 --> 00:08:11.429
If we don't act fast, we may have
to make an emergency landing.

00:08:11.513 --> 00:08:12.722
Then do something!

00:08:13.389 --> 00:08:15.016
A hijacking and turbulence.

00:08:15.850 --> 00:08:19.020
In the middle of the total chaos,
the only relief was that

00:08:19.103 --> 00:08:22.982
Captain Honda Kunihiko was a veteran pilot

00:08:23.066 --> 00:08:24.442
with over 10,000 flight hours.

00:08:24.526 --> 00:08:26.319
The aircraft has stabilized.

00:08:26.903 --> 00:08:28.780
This was supposed to be a domestic flight.

00:08:28.863 --> 00:08:30.698
We can't make it all the way to Pyongyang.

00:08:30.782 --> 00:08:33.785
Without more fuel,
we'll run out and crash halfway.

00:08:36.412 --> 00:08:38.957
Yes, the captain is right.

00:08:39.749 --> 00:08:42.836
For now, why don't we land
at Itazuke Airport as planned

00:08:43.419 --> 00:08:45.213
and request refueling there?

00:08:48.091 --> 00:08:50.051
They're heading to Itazuke?

00:08:50.135 --> 00:08:51.594
Yes, sir.

00:08:51.678 --> 00:08:53.596
I thought they were headed to North Korea.

00:08:53.680 --> 00:08:55.265
Why are they flying to Itazuke?

00:08:55.849 --> 00:08:58.309
Ah. Why indeed?

00:08:59.310 --> 00:09:01.437
Well, we should take measures.

00:09:01.521 --> 00:09:02.730
What kind of measures?

00:09:05.150 --> 00:09:06.151
I mean…

00:09:11.156 --> 00:09:12.866
- Eh?
- Just as the captain intended,

00:09:12.949 --> 00:09:15.910
the plane landed safely at
its original destination, Itazuke Airport.

00:09:15.994 --> 00:09:17.370
ITAZUKE AIRPORT, FUKUOKA, JAPAN

00:09:17.453 --> 00:09:20.540
For a moment, it gave
the passengers some sort of hope

00:09:20.623 --> 00:09:22.500
that this nightmare might soon be over.

00:09:22.584 --> 00:09:24.878
At this point,
nothing has been confirmed.

00:09:24.961 --> 00:09:29.632
Uh, for now, our top priority is
the safety of the passengers.

00:09:29.716 --> 00:09:32.177
How many hijackers are on board?

00:09:32.260 --> 00:09:34.470
Have any passengers
been killed or injured?

00:09:34.554 --> 00:09:35.805
When was the last communication?

00:09:35.889 --> 00:09:37.140
Are the hijackers armed?

00:09:37.223 --> 00:09:40.852
-Is it true they're backed by someone?
-Are all the passengers unharmed?

00:09:46.107 --> 00:09:47.150
Like I said,

00:09:47.650 --> 00:09:51.070
our top priority right now is
the safety of the passengers.

00:09:51.654 --> 00:09:52.989
We want you

00:09:54.741 --> 00:09:56.159
to fill the tanks,

00:09:57.076 --> 00:09:59.829
clear the runway,
and bring us the flight charts right now.

00:10:00.622 --> 00:10:02.916
If you don't give us what we want,

00:10:02.999 --> 00:10:05.877
we'll start killing
the passengers one by one!

00:10:05.960 --> 00:10:08.713
How long would it take
to fill up the tanks?

00:10:08.796 --> 00:10:11.716
Actually, if they're trying
to get to Pyongyang,

00:10:11.799 --> 00:10:13.593
the fuel on board should be enough.

00:10:13.676 --> 00:10:16.262
What are you talking about?
That's not the point.

00:10:16.346 --> 00:10:19.432
If we want to negotiate,
we need to buy as much time as possible.

00:10:28.942 --> 00:10:30.109
Please don't shoot.

00:10:30.193 --> 00:10:32.362
I brought the flight charts you asked for.

00:10:32.445 --> 00:10:33.738
Here they are.

00:10:33.821 --> 00:10:35.198
Move!

00:10:41.913 --> 00:10:43.164
Damn it.

00:10:43.248 --> 00:10:44.624
You think we're idiots?

00:10:44.707 --> 00:10:47.460
No. There wasn't much time,
so we had to prepare them in a rush.

00:10:47.543 --> 00:10:48.962
What about the fuel?

00:10:49.045 --> 00:10:51.839
We're working on it now.
If you could give us a little more time…

00:11:01.099 --> 00:11:02.475
One passenger every hour.

00:11:03.309 --> 00:11:04.978
If you ignore our demands,

00:11:05.645 --> 00:11:06.980
we will kill them.

00:11:07.480 --> 00:11:08.481
Go on.

00:11:15.113 --> 00:11:16.114
Go!

00:11:16.614 --> 00:11:17.615
Yes, sir.

00:11:19.075 --> 00:11:21.327
Hey, just drag one out first.

00:11:21.411 --> 00:11:24.205
What are you doing?
Not without Mr. Yamada's orders.

00:11:24.289 --> 00:11:26.374
The second-in-command gave the go-ahead.

00:11:26.457 --> 00:11:28.418
We agreed to avoid unnecessary bloodshed!

00:11:28.918 --> 00:11:31.754
If the passengers start panicking,
it'll be hard to control them.

00:11:31.838 --> 00:11:33.423
That's the kind of thing

00:11:33.506 --> 00:11:36.384
only weak, college-graduate types
like you worry about.

00:11:37.260 --> 00:11:38.928
What are you standing around for?

00:11:40.138 --> 00:11:42.348
Hey, you. Come here.

00:11:42.432 --> 00:11:44.350
- No, wait! Please don't kill me!
- Come on!

00:11:46.519 --> 00:11:47.562
Yamagata!

00:11:48.646 --> 00:11:50.315
Somebody help me!

00:11:59.907 --> 00:12:00.950
Shut up!

00:12:01.034 --> 00:12:03.036
You want to die in his place?

00:12:04.787 --> 00:12:06.247
Takashi, do it!

00:12:06.789 --> 00:12:07.874
Do it!

00:12:11.669 --> 00:12:13.296
Who the hell are you?

00:12:18.509 --> 00:12:21.679
You need to treat the hostages carefully
until the negotiations are over.

00:12:21.763 --> 00:12:24.307
Since their lives are tied to yours.

00:12:35.860 --> 00:12:38.154
Who the hell are you?
What do you think you're doing?

00:12:39.572 --> 00:12:43.159
Tell your leader I want a word with him.

00:13:02.804 --> 00:13:04.430
You think you can help us?

00:13:05.264 --> 00:13:07.266
How exactly?

00:13:07.975 --> 00:13:11.854
First, let the women, children,
and the elderly go.

00:13:12.522 --> 00:13:13.648
Why should we?

00:13:13.731 --> 00:13:15.983
What you want is a revolution, isn't it?

00:13:17.402 --> 00:13:22.490
As you know, a revolution
without public support is bound to fail.

00:13:23.282 --> 00:13:26.702
But terrorists who release
women and children win favor

00:13:26.786 --> 00:13:28.830
with the public and the press.

00:13:29.664 --> 00:13:32.959
If you make the first move,
all the criticism falls on the government.

00:13:33.543 --> 00:13:38.214
After that, whatever you do,
it's the government that takes the blame.

00:13:39.340 --> 00:13:42.135
In the end, they'll have no choice
but to let you take off.

00:13:44.178 --> 00:13:48.182
And you'll still have
over a hundred hostages.

00:13:49.642 --> 00:13:51.602
Not a bad bargain, is it?

00:13:53.688 --> 00:13:55.148
And then what?

00:13:56.232 --> 00:13:57.942
Once you reach Pyongyang,

00:13:58.025 --> 00:14:00.403
put the remaining passengers and crew
back on the plane

00:14:00.486 --> 00:14:01.863
and send them home to Japan.

00:14:02.947 --> 00:14:06.367
Then the press won't call you hijackers.

00:14:07.034 --> 00:14:10.246
They'll paint you as heroes
who pulled off a bold operation.

00:14:11.956 --> 00:14:12.957
Well, probably.

00:14:17.503 --> 00:14:20.006
We can't just send the plane back.

00:14:21.382 --> 00:14:24.135
We need to make
some kind of gesture to North Korea,

00:14:25.511 --> 00:14:27.221
or they won't take us in.

00:14:29.765 --> 00:14:31.142
I can provide that.

00:14:47.408 --> 00:14:48.451
That's…

00:14:49.452 --> 00:14:50.453
Mr. Yamada.

00:14:51.996 --> 00:14:53.039
I told you.

00:14:53.706 --> 00:14:55.458
I could help you.

00:14:57.585 --> 00:15:00.880
Take a chance and trust me.

00:15:01.380 --> 00:15:05.134
Do as I say, and you'll get what you want
without anyone getting hurt.

00:15:17.647 --> 00:15:19.398
It's opening!

00:15:53.599 --> 00:15:57.144
In the end, they did
what I told them and let 23 passengers go.

00:15:57.228 --> 00:15:59.146
Women, children, and the elderly.

00:16:00.356 --> 00:16:04.568
The meth in my briefcase was worth
nearly 90 million yen on the street,

00:16:04.652 --> 00:16:07.446
and word was all over Japan
that the big shots in Pyongyang

00:16:07.530 --> 00:16:08.990
were crazy for the stuff.

00:16:09.490 --> 00:16:13.828
To these bastards, I was
like a jackpot that fell on their laps.

00:16:13.911 --> 00:16:15.746
They've released 23 passengers in total.

00:16:15.830 --> 00:16:17.832
Women, children, and the elderly.

00:16:17.915 --> 00:16:19.208
They really let them go?

00:16:19.292 --> 00:16:20.293
Yes, sir.

00:16:20.376 --> 00:16:21.627
But…

00:16:21.711 --> 00:16:24.839
they're saying if we don't supply fuel
and clear the runway immediately,

00:16:24.922 --> 00:16:27.008
they'll kill the rest of the passengers.

00:16:27.091 --> 00:16:28.884
- What?
- Kill them?

00:16:29.635 --> 00:16:31.804
-What are we going to do?
-This is a problem.

00:16:32.805 --> 00:16:33.931
This is bad.

00:16:34.015 --> 00:16:35.641
For now, give them what they want.

00:16:35.725 --> 00:16:37.643
The passengers' safety
is our top priority.

00:16:37.727 --> 00:16:38.728
What do we do?

00:16:44.483 --> 00:16:47.111
They're pulling back!
The fighter jets are moving!

00:16:49.238 --> 00:16:51.157
They're letting us take off.

00:16:54.535 --> 00:16:56.537
We're going to Pyongyang!

00:17:05.338 --> 00:17:07.173
They're fueling us up!

00:17:07.256 --> 00:17:09.842
We're going to Pyongyang!

00:17:09.925 --> 00:17:11.594
Let's go to North Korea!

00:17:16.474 --> 00:17:19.560
Why are you helping us?

00:17:20.061 --> 00:17:22.355
It's just better to handle things quietly.

00:17:23.731 --> 00:17:26.150
Nothing good comes
from making a lot of noise, does it?

00:17:27.276 --> 00:17:29.570
Who are you?

00:17:29.654 --> 00:17:30.821
As you can see,

00:17:31.822 --> 00:17:33.366
I'm just a businessman.

00:17:34.325 --> 00:17:35.993
When you say a businessman…

00:17:38.204 --> 00:17:40.331
you mean in this kind of business, huh?

00:17:40.956 --> 00:17:42.500
It's the best money-maker there is.

00:17:42.583 --> 00:17:44.335
Though it comes with its risks.

00:17:46.212 --> 00:17:47.588
Are you with the yakuza?

00:17:48.506 --> 00:17:49.507
No.

00:17:50.508 --> 00:17:52.677
They're more like business partners.

00:17:53.219 --> 00:17:54.261
Something like that.

00:18:00.017 --> 00:18:01.727
Can I bum a cigarette?

00:18:11.195 --> 00:18:12.613
Is that the last one?

00:18:15.866 --> 00:18:18.911
We're basically in the same boat now.

00:18:19.495 --> 00:18:21.163
You can spare me a cigarette, no?

00:18:30.631 --> 00:18:32.717
Oh, boy. It's his last one.

00:18:46.439 --> 00:18:49.525
They say once you get on meth,
you can never quit.

00:18:49.608 --> 00:18:50.818
Have you tried it?

00:18:52.278 --> 00:18:54.989
If you're curious, why don't you
go ahead and try it now?

00:18:58.075 --> 00:19:00.077
We're ready to take off, sir.

00:19:11.922 --> 00:19:18.012
J, A, Y, 3, 5, 1.

00:19:18.721 --> 00:19:23.434
3, 8, 1, 1, 7.

00:19:35.613 --> 00:19:40.159
KOREA GIMPO AIRPORT RAPCON,

00:19:44.580 --> 00:19:46.957
RAPCON is
US Air Force, no Korea!

00:19:47.041 --> 00:19:49.502
Sergeant Chae Jiseok
is going to be here soon, all right?

00:19:49.585 --> 00:19:52.087
He belongs to RAPCON.
Fucking let him deal with it.

00:19:52.922 --> 00:19:55.007
We're not going
to get our hands dirty here.

00:19:57.176 --> 00:19:58.177
Sir.

00:20:02.431 --> 00:20:03.432
You called for me, sir?

00:20:11.148 --> 00:20:13.984
As of this moment,
US Forces Korea will vacate RAPCON

00:20:14.068 --> 00:20:17.363
and take no part in any situation
that may arise going forward.

00:20:18.197 --> 00:20:21.033
Wait, I'm sorry, sir. I don't understand.

00:20:21.742 --> 00:20:23.577
Who's going to be in charge here then?

00:20:24.203 --> 00:20:25.204
Hey.

00:20:26.288 --> 00:20:27.540
Come here.

00:20:33.003 --> 00:20:35.214
Are you the chief controller?

00:20:36.131 --> 00:20:37.132
Yes.

00:20:37.716 --> 00:20:38.884
Rank and name!

00:20:39.677 --> 00:20:42.346
Yes, sir! Sergeant Chae Jiseok.

00:20:53.065 --> 00:20:54.108
Yes, sir.

00:20:55.860 --> 00:20:57.361
Yes, sir. Okay.

00:20:58.320 --> 00:20:59.321
Take it.

00:21:00.656 --> 00:21:01.782
Take it.

00:21:07.955 --> 00:21:10.916
KCIA Director here.
Are you the chief controller?

00:21:11.000 --> 00:21:12.001
Yes, sir!

00:21:12.084 --> 00:21:13.919
The KCIA.

00:21:14.003 --> 00:21:17.047
A state intelligence agency created by
the military regime that seized power

00:21:17.131 --> 00:21:18.883
in a coup to keep its grip on the country.

00:21:18.966 --> 00:21:22.219
Modeled after the US CIA, it operated
under the banner of anti-communism,

00:21:22.303 --> 00:21:24.513
handling national security,
intelligence gathering,

00:21:24.597 --> 00:21:25.890
and covert operations abroad.

00:21:25.973 --> 00:21:28.142
But the reality was different.

00:21:28.726 --> 00:21:33.314
Skirting the law, it terrorized the people
and wielded unchecked power.

00:21:34.023 --> 00:21:37.818
The KCIA was nothing more
than the President's personal guard.

00:21:38.444 --> 00:21:40.779
Listen carefully
to what I'm about to say.

00:21:40.863 --> 00:21:42.406
These are the President's orders.

00:21:42.489 --> 00:21:44.950
In a little while,
a plane will cross over to our side.

00:21:45.451 --> 00:21:49.163
You must seize that plane
before Pyongyang does, no matter what.

00:21:49.246 --> 00:21:52.291
Under no circumstances should you let it
reach Pyongyang first.

00:21:52.374 --> 00:21:53.500
Understood?

00:21:53.584 --> 00:21:54.627
Yes, sir. Understood.

00:22:00.799 --> 00:22:03.761
At last,
the plane left Itazuke Airport

00:22:03.844 --> 00:22:05.137
and headed for Pyongyang.

00:22:08.182 --> 00:22:10.601
But it was imperative that
we never reach Pyongyang

00:22:10.684 --> 00:22:12.686
as the Revolutionary Army wanted.

00:22:14.772 --> 00:22:18.233
It's better to die
than to end up in Pyongyang.

